        "last_activity_date": 1242402224,
        "creation_date": 1242396486,
        "answer_count": 5,
        "title": "How to keep whitespace before document element when parsing with Java?",
        "body": "<p>In my application, I alter some part of XML files, which begin like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n&lt;!-- $Id: version control yadda-yadda $ --&gt;\n\n&lt;myElement&gt;\n...\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note the blank line before <code>&lt;myElement&gt;<\/code>. After loading, altering and saving, the result is far from pleasing:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n&lt;!-- $Id: version control yadda-yadda $ --&gt;&lt;myElement&gt;\n...\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I found out that the whitespace (one newline) between the comment and the document node is not represented in the DOM at all. The following self-contained code reproduces the issue reliably:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String source =\n    \"&lt;?xml version=\\\"1.0\\\" encoding=\\\"UTF-16\\\"?&gt;\\n&lt;!-- foo --&gt;\\n&lt;empty/&gt;\";\nbyte[] sourceBytes = source.getBytes(\"UTF-16\");\n\nDocumentBuilder builder =\n    DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance().newDocumentBuilder();\nDocument doc =\n    builder.parse(new ByteInputStream(sourceBytes, sourceBytes.length));\n\nDOMImplementationLS domImplementation =\n    (DOMImplementationLS) doc.getImplementation();\nLSSerializer lsSerializer = domImplementation.createLSSerializer();\nSystem.out.println(lsSerializer.writeToString(doc));\n\n// output: &lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-16\"?&gt;\\n&lt;!-- foo --&gt;&lt;empty/&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Does anyone have an idea how to avoid this? Essentially, I want the output to be the same as the input. (I know that the xml declaration will be regenerated because it's not part of the DOM, but that's not an issue here.)<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 868887,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "xml",
            "dom",
            "parsing",
            "whitespace"
        ],
